content: What a unique experience this is. It feels very Japanese, reminiscent of games like the Katamari series. They aren't that many levels but they almost all feel unique and memorable. NB: support for taller aspect ratios would be nice, the game only supports 16:9 and taller displays will have to deal with letterboxing.

I wanted to check out what Halegg made out and it's very fun. I spent my entire day on this game and now I'm aiming to get all the medals. It's short but the gameplay is well made and the stages are really fun to mess around with.

Ever since HAL Lab established a sub division dedicated to mobile games, I was curious what their team could come up with. They released Part Time UFO and it genuinely surprised me. Unlike Nintendo's other mobile efforts, HAL Egg managed to make a mobile game which actually feels more like a full length game than whatever Cygames, Nintendo EPD, and DeNA came up with. I cannot stress enough how much great work HAL Egg put into this game. There's just as much little details in this game as their traditional studio's attention to cuteness and detail for Kirby Star Allies' Dream Friend waves (if you haven't checked out Heroes in Another Dimension in wave 3, please do so, it's great). Other reviews already highlight the gameplay and cute graphics, so I want this review to thank HAL for making 2018 wonderful for me 😘.

Hal Labs have outdone themselves once again!  This game is like "The Art of Balance" games mixed with the art style of Rythm Heaven. The result? This awesome little time waster, that's fun, addictive, and just the perfect amount of weird. All the jobs you can do are insanely unique: from stacking cheerleaders, making salads and building machines - there's tons of excitement to be found in this wacky world.  And Hal being Hal, they've created yet another character that I've instantly fallen in love with. Gosh darn it, the little UFO is just too cute for words! Kirby and Boxboy have already melted my heart enough! Now they make THIS little go-getter?  Ugh. I can go on and on about everything I love about this game - the catchy music, the cool old-school style graphics, and all the characters! But, I think I should wrap it up:  This game makes you think - and you've gotta think fast! Plan where to put things, and see how they effect the outcome: if you wanna master everything, then a fair amount of trial and error is needed. After all, things will fall. The only way to go from there is up!  (PS: the game crashes when I try to share with anything but Twitter. It's not taking anything from the experience, and I can never trust my Samsung Galaxy J3 Prime with higher-end games such as these, but... I want that Google Play Achievement. :P)
